archaeological and pictorial evidence, and contemporary literature and legislation. It shows that changes in Irish consumption mirrored changes occurring in England and across Europe and that they were a function of broader developments in the Irish economy, including the increasing participation of Irish merchants in European markets. The book also discusses how consumption was related to wider political, economic and cultural developments in Ireland, showing how the acquisition and interpretation of material goods were key factors in the mediation of political and social boundaries in a semi-colonised and contested society. Susan Flavin completed her doctorate in early modern history at the University of Bristol.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aConsumer goodsxHistoryy16th centuryzIreland. 0aConsumer goodszIrelandxHistoryy16th century. 0aFood habitsxHistoryy16th centuryzIreland. 0aFood habitszIrelandxHistoryy16th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aConsumption.  aCultural Developments.  aEconomic.  aEuropean Markets.  aIrish Merchants.  aMaterial Goods.  aPolitical.  aSixteenth-Century Ireland.  aSociety.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782044093?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044093/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles